revision.text:
'''Nuribeshi''' (漆部司, ぬりべし or ぬりべのつかさ) was an institution under the jurisdiction of the {{ill|Ministry of the Treasury|ja|大蔵省|lt=Ōkurashō|12=draft|12=draft}} in Japan's ancient {{ill|ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft|12=draft}}. According to the {{ill|Shikiinryō|ja|職員令|12=draft|12=draft}}, it oversaw general lacquer-related matters.
== Overview == The Nuribeshi managed lacquerwork on various items such as utensils, Buddhist statues, and paintings, and stored lacquer in a special facility called the ''Urushimuro'' (漆室). The head of this office was titled ''Nuribe no Kami'' (漆部正), supported by other officials such as ''Suke'' (佑) and ''Sakan'' (令史). Additionally, the office employed 20 specialized craftsmen called ''Nuribe'' (漆部), divided into ''Tomobe'' (伴部) and ''Shinabe'' (品部), who were directly involved in lacquer production and exempted from paying {{ill|Chō|ja|調|12=draft|12=draft}} taxes.
According to the ''{{ill|Shōsōin Documents|ja|正倉院文書|lt=Shōsōin Monjo|12=draft|12=draft}}'', records exist indicating the presence of Nuribe units in remote provinces such as {{ill|Izumo Province|ja|出雲国|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Tōtōmi Province|ja|遠江国|12=draft|12=draft}}. The flourishing of Buddhism increased lacquer consumption, prompting regulations requiring the cultivation of 100 lacquer trees for every 300 mulberry trees as part of mandatory labor.
According to the ''{{ill|Ruijū Sandai Kyaku|ja|類聚三代格|12=draft|12=draft}}'', on January 20, 808 ({{ill|Daidō|ja|大同 (日本)|12=draft|12=draft}} year 3), Nuribeshi was merged into the {{ill|Naishōryō|ja|内匠寮|12=draft|12=draft}} of the {{ill|Ministry of Central Affairs|ja|中務省|lt=Nakatsukasa-shō|12=draft|12=draft}}.<ref>{{ill|Ruijū Sandai Kyaku|ja|類聚三代格|12=draft|12=draft}}, Vol. 4 "Addition and Reduction of Officials and Offices," January 20, Daidō year 3.</ref>
== References == {{reflist}}
== Bibliography == * ''Kadokawa Nihonshi Jiten'' (角川第二版日本史辞典), p. 758, edited by {{ill|Takayanagi Mitsutoshi|ja|高柳光寿|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Takeuchi Rizō|ja|竹内理三|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kadokawa Shoten, 1966. * ''Iwanami Nihonshi Jiten'' (岩波日本史辞典), p. 914, supervised by {{ill|Nagahara Keiji|ja|永原慶二|12=draft|12=draft}}, Iwanami Shoten, 1999. * ''Shoku Nihongi 2'' (続日本紀2), Shin Nihon Koten Bungaku Taikei 13, Iwanami Shoten, 1990. * ''Nihon no Rekishi 3: Nara no Miyako'' (日本の歴史3 奈良の都), written by {{ill|Aoki Kazuo|ja|青木和夫|12=draft|12=draft}}, Chūō Kōronsha, 1965. == See Also == * {{ill|Empress Genshō|ja|元正天皇|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Hasebe no Michi Ishikatsu|ja|丈部路石勝|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Hasebe no Michi Sofumaro|ja|丈部路祖父麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Tōdai-ji Vairocana Buddha Statue|ja|東大寺盧舎那仏像|1=Great Buddha of Tōdaiji|12=draft|12=draft}}
