'''Nuribeshi''' (漆部司, ぬりべし or ぬりべのつかさ) was an institution under the jurisdiction of the {{ill|Ministry of the Treasury|ja|大蔵省|lt=Ōkurashō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Japan's ancient {{ill|ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. According to the {{ill|Shikiinryō|ja|職員令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it oversaw general lacquer-related matters.
== Overview == The Nuribeshi managed lacquerwork on various items such as utensils, Buddhist statues, and paintings, and stored lacquer in a special facility called the ''Urushimuro'' (漆室). The head of this office was titled ''Nuribe no Kami'' (漆部正), supported by other officials such as ''Suke'' (佑) and ''Sakan'' (令史). Additionally, the office employed 20 specialized craftsmen called ''Nuribe'' (漆部), divided into ''Tomobe'' (伴部) and ''Shinabe'' (品部), who were directly involved in lacquer production and exempted from paying {{ill|Chō|ja|調|qq=draft|qq=draft}} taxes.
According to the ''{{ill|Shōsōin Documents|ja|正倉院文書|lt=Shōsōin Monjo|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', records exist indicating the presence of Nuribe units in remote provinces such as {{ill|Izumo Province|ja|出雲国|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Tōtōmi Province|ja|遠江国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. The flourishing of Buddhism increased lacquer consumption, prompting regulations requiring the cultivation of 100 lacquer trees for every 300 mulberry trees as part of mandatory labor.
According to the ''{{ill|Ruijū Sandai Kyaku|ja|類聚三代格|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'', on January 20, 808 ({{ill|Daidō|ja|大同 (日本)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} year 3), Nuribeshi was merged into the {{ill|Naishōryō|ja|内匠寮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} of the {{ill|Ministry of Central Affairs|ja|中務省|1=Ministry of the Center|lt=Nakatsukasa-shō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{ill|Ruijū Sandai Kyaku|ja|類聚三代格|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Vol. 4 "Addition and Reduction of Officials and Offices," January 20, Daidō year 3.</ref>
